[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hey everyone. My name is Nick Frediani, artist and photographer from Berlin. Today I\'d like to share a video about me making a digital twin of my car with'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gaussian Splatting, of course. I\'m here in the Hunger Studios in Berlin. I\'ve put some simple top light on my car. Nothing serious, it\'s a very simple'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setup with only one lamp. And I\'ll be walking around my car and taking some picture with Lumix S1H. Wonderful camera not only for filming also taking photographs.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Going to be shooting raw and on a 14 mm lens. Yes, also I\'ll be taking a second data set of a motorbike behind me. Also to showcase the possibilities in'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reconstruction of fine details, fine structures. If you like the video, subscribe or leave a like or comment on the video. If you want to collab, let me know. Write'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an email and I\'ll come back to you. Now have fun with the video. The foundation of high-quality Gaussian Splatting scene lies in capturing sharp, well-exposed images. So good and precise'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photography is essential. Therefore, I took around 200 images in raw format using a tripod. I also stepped down the aperture to increase depth of field.'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'To recover details from the raw photographs, lift the shadows and reduce the highlights. And I increase the contrast quite a bit. As you can see here'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'huge amount of information is lost when shooting in JPEG. And so post-producing your pictures is always a good strategy. Okay, now let\'s take a look at the'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera alignment and the training [music] process. For the alignment I used Reality Scan and for the training I used Lichtfeld Studio. Lichtfeld Studio is a really impressive software for training Gaussian Splats.'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It always delivers really nice, high-quality results. It\'s very intuitive to use, in my opinion. So if you decide to use it, consider supporting the developer, please.'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You find the link below. Since this was a spontaneous idea to scan my car, I did not follow a scanning strategy. I just moved around the car in a circular path at three different heights.'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I also created another image set of my car with the doors open, [music] as you can see here. I moved closer to the open door area to capture more detailed information. And for the bike, I followed the same approach, just'

[02:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'circling it at three different heights and taking additional close-up shots of interesting areas, as you can see here. Okay, let\'s start the training. Okay, the training is done. Let\'s take a'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at the results. As you can see here, the overall reconstruction worked pretty well. The result looks quite impressive, I think. You can inspect the car from all sides and'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even look at details. The windows and other transparent areas did not turn out quite as well, I think. You can still see the reflections, but the reconstruction appears slightly'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'blurry, so there\'s something to improve next time. I trained the same data set using two different strategies, MCMC and MRNF. I hope I pronounced it right. The MCMC'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strategy produces a nice and overall smoother result, I think. But the fine details are not preserved as well as with the MRNF strategy. This delivers much crisper details and'

[04:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a better and sharper look, I think. You can see here. Now let\'s take a look at the motorbike. That is actually my favorite result from the shoot because it\'s turned out'

[04:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exceptionally well. All the details are very sharp and well preserved. You can zoom in very closely to inspect them. I think the lack of highly reflective surfaces is probably one of the reasons'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why it looks so good. I trained this one only with MRNF and I\'m very happy with the result. That\'s the end of this video. In the next one, I\'ll walk you through some key'

[04:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use cases of Gaussian Splatting in automotive marketing from creating [music] product videos and the tools you need to web applications and immersive experience where we can explore a car in XR [music] or VR with'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your headset. Thanks for watching. See you next time.'
